looked all over for shoes like that.

226
00:17:24.600 --> 00:17:29.037
- Wonder why we weren't invited.
- Same reason we weren't invited to the rest.

227
00:17:29.200 --> 00:17:31.589
You can't go to a kids'
party without a kid.

228
00:17:32.520 --> 00:17:37.196
Being a parent is power and once you're
in that circle you keep everyone else out.

229
00:17:37.360 --> 00:17:43.117
Flo. being a parent is about sharing.
It's about a mom. a dad and a kid.

230
00:17:43.280 --> 00:17:48.434
Except there isn't going to be a kid.
Ben. It's just you and me forever.

231
00:17:52.880 --> 00:17:56.270
- Why can't we adopt?
- We've been through this!

232
00:17:56.440 --> 00:18:00.956
I know. but we have so much love to
give. Why waste it on these stupid pets?

233
00:18:01.120 --> 00:18:03.429
They are not stupid!

234
00:18:03.600 --> 00:18:05.238
Hello!

235
00:18:05.400 --> 00:18:10.030
Think of it this way. All those mothers
had to make do with what nature gave them.

236
00:18:10.200 --> 00:18:13.829
You and I get to pick out our
kid. It'll be like shopping.

237
00:18:14.000 --> 00:18:16.912
- Shopping?
- Uh-huh.

238
00:18:17.080 --> 00:18:20.629
But the neighbours will know
we've adopted. What'll they say?

239
00:18:20.800 --> 00:18:23.951
The neighbours? They'll say. "Look!"

240
00:18:24.120 --> 00:18:28.796
"There's Ben and Flo Healy going out to yet
another birthday party with their new son!"

241
00:18:28.960 --> 00:18:31.155
"Isn't he adorable?"

242
00:18:31.320 --> 00:18:34.949
"And look at how fantastic
Flo looks in her new dress!"

243
00:18:35.120 --> 00:18:38.271
"Where did she get a bag
to match those shoes?"

244
00:18:38.440 --> 00:18:42.433
Then they'll say. "Let's invite
that Healy family over for dinner."

245
00:18:42.600 --> 00:18:45.114
Oh. Ben. dinners!

246
00:18:45.280 --> 00:18:47.919
OK. let's get a kid.

247
00:18:48.240 --> 00:18:51.198
Hurry up. students. Five more
minutes for your pen- pals.

248
00:18:51.280 --> 00:18:53.999
Then we have to work
on our times tables.

249
00:18:55.440 --> 00:19:00.468
<i>Dear Queen Elizabeth. how is England?
It must be nice to be a queen.</i>

250
00:19:00.640 --> 00:19:03.313
<i>Dear Bishop Tutu. how are you?</i>

251
00:19:03.480 --> 00:19:07.359
<i>I am fine. I hope everything's
going well with your marching.</i>

252
00:19:07.520 --> 00:19:09.670
<i>Dear Bow Tie Killer. how's prison?</i>

253
00:19:09.840 --> 00:19:14.630
<i>There's a nice picture of you on the front
page that I'm gonna add to my collection.</i>

254
00:19:14.800 --> 00:19:19.954
<i>Even though we've never met. I feel we
have a lot in common. Nobody understands us.</i>

255
00:19:20.120 --> 00:19:24.079
<i>I'm still wearing a bow tie
so I can look just like you.</i>

256
00:19:24.240 --> 00:19:29.439
<i>After all these letters. I've got good
news. I'm getting out. Isn't that great?</i>

257
00:19:29.600 --> 00:19:32.672
<i>Your number one fan. Junior.</i>

258
00:19:41.400 --> 00:19:43.960
Smoke.

259
00:19:50.040 --> 00:19:51.359
Sir.

260
00:19:52.680 --> 00:19:56.753
Sir. sorry to disturb you
but this letter came for you.

261
00:20:01.200 --> 00:20:03.714
Read this to me.

262
00:20:03.880 --> 00:20:06.394
Hey. it's a letter from JR.

263
00:20:06.560 --> 00:20:10.189
Yeah? Someday we're gonna
meet up on the outside.

264
00:20:10.360 --> 00:20:13.113
We're gonna do some serious damage.

265
00:20:13.280 --> 00:20:15.510
"Good news. I'm getting out."

266
00:20:15.680 --> 00:20:20.595
What? He's getting paroled?
They gotta be out of their minds!

267
00:20:20.760 --> 00:20:23.115
You know that guy?
He's crazier than I am.

268
00:20:23.280 --> 00:20:25.191
Chill. The warden!

269
00:20:25.960 --> 00:20:31.592
Well. well! If it isn't our model prisoner.
looking so pretty today in his little bow tie!

270
00:20:31.760 --> 00:20:33.876
Hey. warden! Catch!

271
00:20:37.680 --> 00:20:41.559
I hope I'm not rushing you. We can
always let nature take its course.

272
00:20:41.720 --> 00:20:45.599
Nature screwed us over.
Let's give commerce a try.

273
00:20:47.400 --> 00:20:52.633
Let's see what I can do. You want a kid you
could love. I'll put you on the waiting list.

274
00:20:52.800 --> 00:20:55.155
You should have a kid in seven years.

275
00:20:55.320 --> 00:20:57.550
- Seven years?
- Unless...

276
00:20:57.720 --> 00:21:01.998
Nah. nah. I didn't say a
word. I did not say a word.

277
00:21:02.160 --> 00:21:05.152
No. what? What were you gonna say?

278
00:21:05.320 --> 00:21:10.678
Well. I really put my foot in my mouth
this time but. I don't know. I like you two.

279
00:21:10.840 --> 00:21:15.630
I like the two of you and when I like
two people. I want to help them out.

280
00:21:15.800 --> 00:21:20.351
That's just my nature. I want
to help out people that I like.

281
00:21:20.520 --> 00:21:24.479
Just this morning I came
upon a seven- year- old.

282
00:21:24.640 --> 00:21:29.589
Smart as a tack. a little rambunctious
but weren't we all at that age?

283
00:21:31.120 --> 00:21:33.873
I think I even have
a photo here for you.

284
00:21:34.640 --> 00:21:36.835
He does look presentable
in that bow tie.

285
00:21:37.000 --> 00:21:38.638
Adorable!

286
00:21:38.800 --> 00:21:43.476
I don't know. Seven is rather old. I wanted
people to think I had the baby myself.

287
00:21:43.640 --> 00:21:47.997
That's understandable. A lot of women feel
that way. You want a cute little infant.

288
00:21:48.160 --> 00:21:50.993
One that will scream in
the middle of the night

289
00:21:51.160 --> 00:21:56.029
and you'll have to stumble downstairs in
the dark and change his soiled diapers.

290
00:21:56.200 --> 00:21:58.919
You'll do your
housework. eat chocolates.

291
00:21:59.080 --> 00:22:02.709
take care of the kid and
you'll put on 50 or 60 pounds.

292
00:22:02.880 --> 00:22:03.869
No diapers?

293
00:22:04.040 --> 00:22:07.237
You like to sleep late. There'd
be no baby waking you up.

294
00:22:07.400 --> 00:22:12.679
We could skip all that baby junk and
move right into the good stuff like...

295
00:22:12.840 --> 00:22:15.354
...parties and more parties!

296
00:22:15.520 --> 00:22:17.750
I could be president
of the PTA by September!

297
00:22:17.920 --> 00:22:22.277
- Fuzzball will have someone to play with.
- Yes! Fuzzball's our cat.

298
00:22:22.440 --> 00:22:26.194
I can't believe it!
Junior. he loves cats.

299
00:22:26.360 --> 00:22:29.033
Do you hear that? Let's do it.

300
00:22:29.200 --> 00:22:31.919
Mr Peabody. you've got yourself a deal.

301
00:22:32.080 --> 00:22:33.991
And you've got yourself a kid.

302
00:22:40.880 --> 00:22:44.156
Here he comes. Flo. that's our son.

303
00:22:46.120 --> 00:22:48.839
Can you believe it? That's our boy.

304
00:22:49.000 --> 00:22:52.549
He's very handsome. I'll be
the envy of the neighbourhood.

305
00:22:52.720 --> 00:22:55.518
They look like a couple of yahoos.

306
00:22:58.760 --> 00:22:59.749
Hi!

307
00:23:01.000 --> 00:23:02.433
I think I'm gonna cry.

308
00:23:02.600 --> 00:23:05.637
<i>You ever seen a grown
man wear so much blue?</i>

309
00:23:05.800 --> 00:23:08.234
Hey there. little buddy.

310
00:23:08.400 --> 00:23:11.631
I'm Ben. this is Flo.
Put it there. partner.

311
00:23:11.800 --> 00:23:14.837
My name's Junior. My favourite
colour's blue. What's yours?

312
00:23:16.360 --> 00:23:19.591
My favourite colour's blue.
too. Can you believe...?

313
00:23:19.760 --> 00:23:23.036
He's perfect. He's wonderful. Come here.

314
00:23:23.200 --> 00:23:26.272
Thank you. sisters.
goodbye. Goodbye. kids!

315
00:23:26.440 --> 00:23:29.079
Bye. everybody! Don't forget to write!

316
00:23:35.400 --> 00:23:39.154
We got the pick of the litter.
Everyone's come out to see him off.

317
00:23:59.160 --> 00:24:01.549
Here we are! Isn't this exciting?

318
00:24:01.720 --> 00:24:06.111
Right. everybody out.
This is gonna be so great!

319
00:24:06.280 --> 00:24:12.116
OK. now. everybody over by the house.
This is Junior's first day at his new home.

320
00:24:12.280 --> 00:24:14.589
OK. I want everyone over. Come on.

321
00:24:14.760 --> 00:24:18.639
Junior. put your suitcase down
here. Darling. I want you to hug him.

322
00:24:18.800 --> 00:24:21.758
A lot of teeth. I want
everybody to be happy.

323
00:24:21.920 --> 00:24:25.595
- Smile and say. "cheese doodles!"
- Cheese doodles!

324
00:24:25.760 --> 00:24:28.194
That's great. that's terrific.

325
00:24:28.360 --> 00:24:33.070
How come you adopted me? How
come you just didn't have a baby?

326
00:24:33.240 --> 00:24:35.595
Well. gee...

327
00:24:35.760 --> 00:24:39.639
With a baby. you never know what
you're getting. It could be a dud.

328
00:24:39.800 --> 00:24:42.075
But with you there's no surprise.

329
00:24:42.240 --> 00:24:44.913
- Mr Peabody told us how terrific you are.
- He did?

330
00:24:45.080 --> 00:24:49.596
Sure. He said that you were voted
most popular orphan two years in a row.

331
00:24:49.760 --> 00:24:51.955
That was smart of him.

332
00:24:53.360 --> 00:24:58.150
- In we go.
- Wow. This is a great house.

333
00:24:58.320 --> 00:25:01.517
We're going to keep it
neat and clean. aren't we?

334
00:25:06.520 --> 00:25:08.795
I hope you guys are insured.

335
00:25:10.520 --> 00:25:15.196
And you have a cat. Here. kitty-kitty.

336
00:25:15.360 --> 00:25:20.036
No. Junior. make nice with
kitty. Only pet her this way.

337
00:25:20.200 --> 00:25:23.272
I've never seen Fuzzball act like that.

338
00:25:23.440 --> 00:25:26.432
Junior. come here. I
want you to meet Polly.

339
00:25:26.600 --> 00:25:31.355
- Polly. say hello to Junior.
- Hello. Hello.

340
00:25:31.520 --> 00:25:33.954
Is that the only word he knows?

341
00:25:34.120 --> 00:25:37.430
- Yes. I want to show
you the house. - Uh-oh!

342
00:25:39.360 --> 00:25:43.148
- Do I get my own bed?
- This is the big time! You get your own room!

343
00:25:43.320 --> 00:25:46.517
- Wow!
- I hope you like clowns.

344
00:25:50.520 --> 00:25:52.829
<i>Oh. my God. They're retarded.</i>

345
00:25:53.800 --> 00:25:55.791
So. what do you think. big guy?

346
00:25:55.960 --> 00:25:59.396
Well. there sure are a lot of clowns.

347
00:26:02.080 --> 00:26:06.835
That must be your new grandpa. You stay
here. We'll give old gramps a big surprise.

348
00:26:07.000 --> 00:26:08.319
Sh!

349
00:26:15.520 --> 00:26:17.476
Dad. are we glad to see you.

350
00:26:17.640 --> 00:26:20.996
What's this big surprise
you dragged me over here for?

351
00:26:21.160 --> 00:26:24.516
Well. Dad. here's a hint.

352
00:26:25.840 --> 00:26:28.991
Oh. my God.

353
00:26:29.160 --> 00:26:30.957
Finally.

354
00:26:31.680 --> 00:26:35.753
You've both cooked up a cute
little kid for my campaign!

355
00:26:35.920 --> 00:26:39.799
I thought you were getting fatter.
Mama! When's my little grandson due?

356
00:26:39.960 --> 00:26:44.317
- Fatter?
- No. Dad. Florence is not gonna have a baby.

357
00:26:45.000 --> 00:26:46.752
You rascal. you!

358
00:26:46.920 --> 00:26:51.789
You followed my advice and took your sperm
to somebody who knows what to do with it.

359
00:26:51.960 --> 00:26:53.154
a surrogate mother.

360
00:26:53.320 --> 00:26:59.156
Tell me something. Do you make out with a
cup or do you get to bump a real live one?

361
00:26:59.320 --> 00:27:01.072
No. Dad. we adopted.

362
00:27:01.240 --> 00:27:03.515
Are you insane?

363
00:27:04.760 --> 00:27:07.069
I thought you'd be happy. Come on.

364
00:27:07.240 --> 00:27:10.073
You don't know what you're
letting yourself in for.

365
00:27:10.240 --> 00:27:12.800
Dopehead mothers. Garbage blood.

366
00:27:12.960 --> 00:27:15.952
His parents may have met in a
loony bin. They might be Democrats.

367
00:27:16.120 --> 00:27:20.716
He's a beautiful kid. Once you meet
him. you'll love him like your very own.

368
00:27:20.880 --> 00:27:25.351
I would like to proudly present the
newest member of the Healy family. Junior!

369
00:27:26.680 --> 00:27:28.477
No! Junior!

370
00:27:28.640 --> 00:27:31.313
That's a thousand-dollar coat!

371
00:27:31.480 --> 00:27:34.631
- Junior. are you in here?
- Junior!

372
00:27:34.800 --> 00:27:38.270
Oh. my God. It's the devil.

373
00:27:38.440 --> 00:27:41.796
- Buddy. are you OK?
- Yeah. just a little smoky.

374
00:27:43.680 --> 00:27:47.593
Look. here's the problem. This
clown must have shorted out.

375
00:27:47.760 --> 00:27:51.116
Sparks were coming out of
his nose. I was so scared.

376
00:27:51.280 --> 00:27:54.750
- Little punk is lying.
- Dad!

377
00:27:54.920 --> 00:27:58.959
I hope you kept the damn receipt.
You got one bad seed there.

378
00:27:59.120 --> 00:28:02.908
He can hear you. You'll hurt his
feelings. It was just an accident.

379
00:28:03.080 --> 00:28:06.629
- Accident! Get rid of him.
- We've made our decision.

380
00:28:06.800 --> 00:28:10.679
OK. but it's the last time
I set foot in this house.

381
00:28:20.440 --> 00:28:22.431
Come on. boys.

382
00:28:22.600 --> 00:28:25.478
- Get back.
- What's happening?

383
00:28:25.640 --> 00:28:28.154
Get rid of that kid!

384
00:28:29.440 --> 00:28:32.637
- Get rid of him.
- Easy!

385
00:28:33.680 --> 00:28:36.319
Get rid of that kid!

386
00:28:41.320 --> 00:28:44.517
Poor Fuzzball. She'll never be the same.

387
00:28:44.680 --> 00:28:46.272
Are you ser...

388
00:28:46.440 --> 00:28:49.796
Is that all you can think
of is your stupid cat?

389
00:28:49.960 --> 00:28:55.717
What about the fact that Father's on his way to
the hospital? Or Junior's traumatic first day?

390
00:28:55.880 --> 00:28:57.871
Did you think about the poor boy?

391
00:28:58.040 --> 00:28:59.951
He must feel horrible.

392
00:29:02.080 --> 00:29:04.594
<i>Yeah. but this might
make me feel better.</i>

393
00:29:05.600 --> 00:29:09.070
Fifty. sixty. seventy...

394
00:29:15.520 --> 00:29:17.590
I see a furry bunny.

395
00:29:18.920 --> 00:29:24.074
A furry bunny is running through
delicate white snowflakes.

396
00:29:24.240 --> 00:29:26.754
He's lying. That's not what he sees.

397
00:29:26.920 --> 00:29:31.118
I'm sorry. I'm conducting an
examination. Now what do you see. Martin?

398
00:29:31.280 --> 00:29:33.714
I see a meadow. Pink flowers.

399
00:29:33.880 --> 00:29:39.034
He's lying again. How can he see pink? It's
a black and white picture. There is no pink.

400
00:29:39.200 --> 00:29:42.431
Warden. if you don't stop.
I'll have to ask you to leave.

401
00:29:42.600 --> 00:29:44.431
There is no pink.

402
00:29:46.640 --> 00:29:49.279
I see white fluffy clouds...

403
00:29:49.440 --> 00:29:52.591
No. you don't! You see
murder! You see guts!

404
00:29:52.760 --> 00:29:54.876
I'm going to ask you to leave!

405
00:29:55.040 --> 00:29:58.396
Those damn liberal laws! Don't
you understand? He sees blood!

406
00:29:58.560 --> 00:30:00.551
No. that's what you see.

407
00:30:03.080 --> 00:30:05.753
I am so sorry about that. Martin.

408
00:30:06.640 --> 00:30:10.394
Now. let's get back to
our examination. Shall we?

409
00:30:10.560 --> 00:30:12.437
What do you see in this one?

410
00:30:12.600 --> 00:30:15.068
I see...

411
00:30:15.240 --> 00:30:17.037
...blood!

412
00:30:23.120 --> 00:30:26.954
- Doc. how did it go with the star patient?
- Oh. that guy.

413
00:30:27.120 --> 00:30:30.157
There's a few bricks
missing from his building.

414
00:30:59.680 --> 00:31:03.514
- Hey. what are you doing?
- Nothing.

415
00:31:03.680 --> 00:31:04.954
Gosh. what happened here?

416
00:31:05.120 --> 00:31:09.830
I was looking for some paper to write a get
- well note to Big Ben.

417
00:31:10.000 --> 00:31:14.516
That's very thoughtful. Junior.
but these are Mom's private drawers.

418
00:31:14.680 --> 00:31:18.559
You shouldn't go in there. It's where
she keeps her needlepoint and crochet.

419
00:31:29.680 --> 00:31:34.276
I'm really sorry. Mr Healy. I was
scared being all alone in my room.

420
00:31:36.000 --> 00:31:38.036
Of course.

421
00:31:38.200 --> 00:31:42.716
I understand why you're scared. This
is your first night in your new home.

422
00:31:42.880 --> 00:31:46.316
It's gonna take some
getting used to. isn't it?

423
00:31:46.480 --> 00:31:52.430
You know. Junior. I'm a little scared
myself. This is my first night being a dad.

424
00:31:52.600 --> 00:31:56.434
- You'll learn quick enough.
- Learn what?

425
00:31:56.600 --> 00:32:00.559
What it's like to be a dad.
Then you'll get rid of me.

426
00:32:01.560 --> 00:32:06.759
Get rid of you? Junior. We're never
gonna get rid of you. You're here forever.

427
00:32:06.920 --> 00:32:09.434
We're gonna do everything together.

428
00:32:09.600 --> 00:32:13.149
We'll ride bikes. go
fishing. play catch.

429
00:32:13.320 --> 00:32:16.630
I want to be a good dad.
I want to be a great dad.

430
00:32:16.800 --> 00:32:18.119
You know what?

431
00:32:18.280 --> 00:32:20.669
I will never be too busy to sit down

432
00:32:20.840 --> 00:32:25.391
and listen to what's on my son's
mind over a cup of hot cocoa.

433
00:32:31.720 --> 00:32:35.508
Hey. sleepyhead. Y'all
ready to go camping?

434
00:32:35.680 --> 00:32:39.195
I was planning on watching cartoons.

435
00:32:39.360 --> 00:32:41.430
Don't be such a noodle.

436
00:32:41.600 --> 00:32:46.754
When I was your age. your grandfather
was always too busy to take me camping.

437
00:32:46.920 --> 00:32:49.070
You are a lucky duck.

438
00:32:49.240 --> 00:32:52.277
Ben! Bring him.

439
00:32:53.200 --> 00:32:58.752
- Come here. I want you to meet someone.
- Mrs Henderson! And little Miss Lucy!

440
00:32:58.920 --> 00:33:00.911
What a nice surprise!

441
00:33:01.080 --> 00:33:06.916
We heard about your little accident and we
thought this fruitcake might cheer you up.

442
00:33:07.760 --> 00:33:09.830
Thank you!

443
00:33:10.000 --> 00:33:13.276
I would like you to meet my son Junior.

444
00:33:13.440 --> 00:33:16.398
- Pleased to meet you. ladies.
- Oh. my!

445
00:33:16.560 --> 00:33:19.632
He's a perfect little
gentleman. Isn't he. Lucy?

446
00:33:19.800 --> 00:33:21.552
He's so big.

447
00:33:21.720 --> 00:33:25.918
Yesterday they didn't even have a kid
and now they have a seven-year-old.

448
00:33:26.080 --> 00:33:28.355
That's gross.

449
00:33:28.520 --> 00:33:32.479
- I don't want him at my party.
- Lucy.

450
00:33:32.640 --> 00:33:38.078
But. Mother. he dresses like
the man that cremated Uncle Leo.

451
00:33:38.240 --> 00:33:40.674
Lucy's turning six this week

452
00:33:40.840 --> 00:33:45.118
but I don't think we'll
have a clown this year.

453
00:33:45.280 --> 00:33:48.670
Or balloons. Or ice cream.

454
